outputs.output_descr:
-	Change in behavior of military personal: increased discipline, respect for human rights and political neutrality leading to a decrease of the instances of human rights violations vis a vis the civilian population as a result of:
o	Rehabilitation of 17 military camps, reforestation and the relocation of 723 families to their places of origin, leading to a return of 90% of military forces to barracks; 
o	Closing of 95% of the military positions having a direct impact on security situation in rural areas;
o	Return of 16,500 arms and munitions to military armories, leading to increased control of stocks; 
-	Increased knowledge of the code of conduct and understanding of the impact of gender, Aids, hygiene, leadership and human rights in the security sector. These dimensions are now fully part of the training of the FDN due to the organization of mass training programme to support military: reaching 1,650 officers (83%), 4,050 under officers (94%) and 16,080 soldiers (86%);
-	Improved image of the Burundian army and an increased belief in their mission as well as willingness to cooperate by supporting the reconciliation between the army and the civilian population; 
-	Provision of temporary employment to vulnerable local populations (35% of which were women).

